observation.text:
Pxxx24-NOV-9728-NOV-9728-NOV-97HASANADKA,MANGALA DCOBBS,ELIZABETH JMEDICINEB4_OBSvolume lossxxyr old xx xxDOA: 11/24/97
DOD: 11/28/97
DX: Acute renal failure
Dehydration
Small bowel obstruction
Procedures: none
Consults: none
H&P: please see admit note
Hospital Course: The patient is a xx yo xx with a history of multi-infarct dementia, HTN, CAD, and PUD s/p Bilroth II who presented from her nursing home with mental status changes and vomitting.
1. ARF: There was a noticable change from her baseline dementia, which was secondary to an acute renal failure. Her initial BUN and Cr were 61 and 4.2 respectively. The patient was dehydrated as she had been vomitting secondary to a small bowel obstruction. The patient was treated with aggressive hydration. She was initially bolused with 1L of fluid and then given a continuous drip. The following morning, her BUN and Cr did not change. She was then bolused with another liter in addition to her maintainance rate. Her BUN and Cr slowly began to decrease and her mental status began to improve. On the day of discharge, her BUN and Cr were 17 and 1.0.
2. Small bowel obstruction: The patient was treated with bowel rest. She was made NPO and and NG tube was placed. She received a tap water enema without effect. She then received 2 phosphate enemas to which she had bowel movements. Her abdominal distention improved. A repeat KUB showed much improvement. She was begun on a clear liquid diet, which she was she tolerated. Then she was advanced to a mechanically soft diet, which she also tolerated.
3. Leukocytosis: At admission the patient had a WBC of 17.0. This was thought to be secondary to volume contraction as a source was not found, and the patient was afebrile. Over the hospital course, her WBC did decrease. 4. HTN: The patient's anti-hypertensive medications were held as she was NPO. Her pressure was controlled with a nitroglycerin patch. As her volume status improved, her blood pressure began to increase. She was re-started on her home anti-HTN medications once she was able to have o
ral intake.
5. PUD: The patient's NG tube suctioned what was coffee ground emesis. She was place on a continuous cimetidine drip. The suction cleared. She will be dicharged on po cimetidine. Her CBC will be drawn in 3 days to follow her hemoglobin. Consider EGD.
